(a)  Default (room-temperature) run  
With 15 A and 10 BC at the preset “Initial Temperature,” only an occasional A-BC collision has enough energy to get over the activation-energy hump that you can see on the potential-energy diagram.  Most encounters therefore end in an elastic bounce and the numbers of A and BC on the bar-chart hardly change.  Only a few AB + C molecules appear in a fairly long period of simulated time, so the reaction rate is decidedly slow.

(b)  High-temperature run  
After resetting, raise the Initial Temperature until the green “total average energy” line on the graph sits completely above the red potential-energy curve (the barrier).  Now every collision between A and BC possesses more than enough energy to break the B–C bond and form AB + C.  Visually you see:

• the BC molecules disappear almost immediately;  
• AB and C counts climb to 10 (the original amount of BC) in just a few tenths of a second of simulation time;  
• the bar chart and the particle view change very rapidly;  
• the reaction essentially goes to completion and then stops because no BC is left.

So, when the temperature is raised high enough to put the average molecular energy above the activation energy, the reaction that was slow at the lower temperature becomes extremely fast—practically instantaneous in the simulation.

